      "content": "A scholar making this argument might counter that the notion of \"national identity\" is itself a product of the very social contract that gives rise to the state. The idea that border control is merely about excluding national identity can be seen as a form of ideological compromise, glossing over the historical and ongoing power dynamics that shape an nation's conception of itself.\n\nThey might argue that by prioritizing cultural homogeneity over the complexities of human experience, proponents of strict border control are in fact creating artificial boundaries between differing groups, rather than acknowledging and working to minimize conflicts. This analogy can be grounded in the work of scholars such as Benedict Anderson, who has discussed the relationship between nationalism and citizenship in this context.",
